Comprehensive Final PhD Proposal: AI‑Driven Martian Subsurface Access

---

Abstract

The InSight mission's HP³ "mole" was designed to penetrate 3–5 m into the Martian subsurface to measure planetary heat flow. Instead, an unexpected cohesive duricrust layer, formed by brine‑efflorescence cementation, prevented regolith from flowing around the probe. Without the required hull friction, the mole achieved only ≈37 cm—an order of magnitude short of its target—and repeatedly bounced out of its hole. Recent coupled FDM‑DEM simulations confirm that porosity, density, ice content and mechanical vibration critically affect penetration resistance under Martian gravity.

This failure exposes a fundamental gap: current mission planning cannot reliably predict subsurface mechanical properties from orbital data, and penetrators cannot autonomously adapt to unforeseen soil conditions. This PhD research develops a purely theoretical and computational framework that closes this gap through advanced mathematical modelling and AI‑architecture design. No physical experiments, hardware prototyping or terrestrial‑analog testing will be conducted.

The framework comprises three integrated tiers:

1. Tier 1 – Multi‑Modal Variational Transformer (MMVT) with Bayesian outputs: probabilistic pre‑landing prediction of duricrust occurrence, thickness and mechanical strength from orbital remote‑sensing data (HiRISE, CRISM, THEMIS, SHARAD), trained on real mission data augmented with 10⁴ synthetic DEM samples calibrated to InSight and UPRS‑1 simulant parameters.
2. Tier 2 – Multi‑Fidelity Bayesian Inverse Terramechanics: extraction of regolith mechanical properties (cohesion c, friction angle \phi, pressure‑sinkage modulus K) from existing rover telemetry (wheel slip, sinkage, motor current, drill feed resistance) using Deep Gaussian Processes (DGP) with inducing points, following the validated Fediukov (2025) framework.
3. Tier 3 – Momentum‑Conserving Graph‑Network Surrogate with Risk‑Sensitive Reinforcement Learning: a differentiable GNN surrogate (DYNAMI‑CAL GRAPHNET) that enforces hard conservation of linear and angular momentum for real‑time penetration‑dynamics prediction, coupled with a Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO) controller trained entirely in simulation with domain randomisation for autonomous adaptive penetration.

The three tiers are unified through Bayesian uncertainty propagation, enabling risk‑aware decision‑making from orbit to subsurface with explicit Value‑at‑Risk (VaR) and Conditional Value‑at‑Risk (CVaR) quantification. All validation relies on cross‑validation with existing mission datasets, comparison against published DEM benchmarks (LIGGGHTS/YADE), and formal calibration metrics (ECE, coverage probability). The research will deliver: (1) the first comprehensive Martian Regolith Penetration Database with labelled mechanical properties and corresponding orbital signatures; (2) a validated differentiable GNN surrogate for penetrator–soil interaction with hard momentum‑conservation guarantees; (3) a risk‑sensitive RL control policy for adaptive penetration; and (4) a blueprint for flight‑software architecture deployable on space‑grade hardware (XQR Versal AI Core). This work will transform subsurface access from a high‑risk empirical gamble into a predictable, mathematically rigorous engineering discipline.

