1. Introduction and Motivation

1.1 The InSight HP³ Failure: A Mission‑Critical Gap

The Heat Flow and Physical Properties Package (HP³) aboard NASA’s InSight lander was designed to hammer a 40 cm‑long "mole" to a depth of 3–5 m to measure Mars’ internal heat flow—a primary science objective constraining planetary thermal‑evolution models. The design assumed a cohesionless, sand‑like regolith that would flow around the probe, providing frictional resistance to counteract recoil from the internal hammer mechanism.

Post‑deployment, the mole penetrated less than 40 cm and repeatedly bounced out of its hole. Analysis revealed an unexpectedly thick, cohesive duricrust layer ≈20 cm thick with measured penetration resistance of 0.3–0.7 MPa, overlying material with resistance 4.9 \pm 0.4 MPa below 30 cm depth. Estimated cohesion ranged from 2–15 kPa depending on internal friction angle.

The duricrust formation mechanism has been refined by subsequent thermal measurements: temperatures in the top 40 cm of Martian soil promote the formation of crusty salt films through brine efflorescence, which crystallise and cement soil grains together. Yet thermal‑conductivity measurements from HP³ itself show strong correlation with atmospheric pressure (6.5 % per mbar), characteristic of unconsolidated material with values ≈0.038 W m⁻¹ K⁻¹. This apparent contradiction is resolved by recognising that the duricrust is a thin, cemented surface layer that disaggregated during initial penetration attempts, while deeper material, though unconsolidated, presents high resistance due to confining pressure and grain packing rather than cementation.

Despite a nearly two‑year recovery campaign using the lander’s robotic arm to scrape soil and apply side pressure, the final depth was only ≈37 cm—an order of magnitude short of the target. The lessons‑learned report recommended roughly doubling instrument mass for future designs.

1.2 FDM‑DEM Validation of Penetration Dynamics

Recent coupled Finite Difference Method–Discrete Element Method (FDM‑DEM) simulations have validated that porosity, density, and ice content critically affect penetration resistance under Martian conditions. Furthermore, mechanical vibration—exactly the hammering mechanism employed by HP³—can substantially improve penetration efficiency when properly tuned to soil properties, an effect more pronounced in Martian gravity than on Earth. These findings underscore both the complexity of the regolith–penetrator interaction and the opportunity for intelligent adaptive control.

1.3 Quantitative Mass Trade‑Off

The brute‑force approach—doubling instrument mass—is not scalable for diverse future subsurface missions constrained by launch mass.

Approach Mass Penalty Est. Success Probability Mass Efficiency
Brute‑force (2× HP³ mass) +100 % ≈90 % (duricrust < 30 cm) 0.45 per kg
AI‑driven adaptive system +5–10 % ≈75–85 % (adapts) 0.75–0.85 per kg

Intelligent, adaptive systems provide superior mass‑efficiency for missions where every kilogram is critical.

1.4 Broader Implications

Subsurface access is essential for:

· Measuring Mars’ internal heat flow (constraining planetary thermal evolution);
· Searching for extant or extinct life (deep regolith may harbour radiation‑protected biosignatures);
· Extracting water ice for ISRU propellant and life support (ice expected at > 1 m depth in mid‑latitudes);
· Emplacing seismic sensors for future networks.

The HP³ failure demonstrates that current design methodologies cannot reliably predict regolith mechanical behaviour. Until this gap is closed, any mission requiring subsurface penetration carries unacceptable risk.

1.5 Mapping to 2030–2040 Mission Concepts

The framework directly supports upcoming mission concepts:

· Tier 1 → Mars 2030–2040 heat‑flow/geophysics landers (e.g., Mars Life Explorer, ICE‑MARS‑style concepts);
· Tier 2 → Mars Sample Return, Perseverance‑class rovers, and future ISRU scouts;
· Tier 3 → 2030+ penetrator‑based seismometers or ice‑core probes.

Quantitative risk: if no predictive model is used, the expected probability of < 2 m penetration at a Mars 2030 landing site similar to Elysium can be as high as 40–60 %; our framework aims to reduce this to < 15 % at fixed mass.

