2. Research Gap and Current Limitations

2.1 Current Limitations

1. No Pre‑Deployment Characterisation: No validated method exists to predict penetration resistance before deployment. Thermal‑inertia mapping can suggest duricrust presence but cannot quantify mechanical strength. The pre‑landing assessment for InSight predicted "cohesionless sand or low cohesion soils" based on thermal inertia of 200 J/(m² K s¹/²) and albedo 0.25—a prediction that proved incorrect.
2. Empirical Models Based on Terrestrial Analogs: Existing penetrator–soil interaction models derive from terrestrial soils that differ fundamentally from Martian duricrust in cementation mechanism, grain morphology and stress history.
3. Orbital Remote‑Sensing Inability: The relationship between remotely sensed parameters (thermal inertia, albedo, surface texture, polygonal terrain patterns) and in‑situ mechanical properties (cohesion, penetration resistance) remains unknown.

2.2 Contrast with Lunar/Asteroid Inversion Frameworks

While multi‑fidelity GPs and lunar/asteroid regolith datasets exist (e.g., Zhang et al. 2025; lunar/asteroid databases), no Martian penetrator‑focused inversion exists, and none of these systems are coupled end‑to‑end from orbital hazard mapping to RL‑controlled penetration.

2.3 Why ML‑Only is Necessary

Physics‑only models (Bekker‑Wong, DEM) fail at both ends: Bekker‑Wong underestimates Mars duricrust cohesion; DEM is too slow for real‑time control. This sets up Tier 2’s DGP and Tier 3’s GNN‑surrogate as necessary, not merely "nice‑to‑have."

2.4 The Knowledge Gap

No validated predictive model exists for Martian regolith penetration resistance as a function of depth, location and duricrust properties. Without this, any future subsurface probe faces the same uncertainty that doomed HP³.

2.5 Scope and Constraints of This Research

This PhD research is purely theoretical and computational. We will not:

· Conduct physical experiments or hardware testing;
· Build or test penetrator prototypes;
· Perform terrestrial‑analog field campaigns;
· Collect new in‑situ data.

All validation relies on existing published datasets, computational cross‑validation, and comparison with established simulation methods. Deliverables are mathematical models, algorithms, software architectures, and a validated simulation framework.

