4. Tier 1: Probabilistic Pre‑Landing Duricrust Prediction

4.1 Objective

Develop a deep‑learning model that produces probabilistic hazard maps for duricrust occurrence, thickness and expected mechanical strength using only orbital remote‑sensing data, with calibrated uncertainty bounds.

4.2 Data Scarcity Challenge and Solution

Challenge: Labelled mechanical properties from orbital data are extremely limited—only ~10–15 landing sites with sparse telemetry. Direct training on this dataset risks severe overfitting.

Solution: Augment the real dataset with 10⁴ synthetic samples generated from calibrated DEM simulations (LIGGGHTS/YADE) using parameter distributions derived from:

· InSight HP³ measurements: c \sim \mathcal{U}(0,25) kPa, \phi \sim \mathcal{U}(20^\circ,45^\circ);
· UPRS‑1 simulant parameters for Utopia Planitia duricrust (hydrated sulfates, opaline silica cementation).

4.3 Architecture: Multi‑Modal Variational Transformer (MMVT)

Encoder Branches:

· Vision Branch (HiRISE imagery): Vision Transformer (ViT) with patch size P \times P (e.g., 16 \times 16 pixels at 25 cm/px → 4 m spatial patches). Sequence of N_p = \frac{H \times W}{P^2} patches passes through L transformer layers with multi‑head self‑attention.
· Spectral Branch (CRISM hyperspectral): 3D convolutional frontend followed by a Selectable Self‑Attention Spectral Feature Extraction Module (S3FE‑Module) that applies salient feature selection to remove noise channels and extracts unique channel‑sequence features via transformer encoding.
· Thermal/Topographic Branch: MLP encoders with sinusoidal positional encoding process scalar fields (thermal inertia from THEMIS, elevation, slope).

Cross‑Modal Fusion:
A Cross‑Transformer Feature Fusion Strategy (CTF) uses multi‑head attention across modalities, analogous to the transformer‑based multi‑modal fusion validated for Martian crater classification (Yang et al. 2026):

\mathbf{Z}_{\text{fused}} = \text{CrossAttention}(\mathbf{Z}_{\text{vision}}, \mathbf{Z}_{\text{spectral}}, \mathbf{Z}_{\text{thermal}})

\text{CrossAttention}(Q, K, V) = \text{softmax}\!\left(\frac{QK^T}{\sqrt{d_k}}\right)V

Bayesian Output Layer:
Deterministic regression heads are replaced with Monte Carlo Dropout for uncertainty quantification. The predictive distribution is:

p(\mathbf{y} | \mathbf{x}, \mathbf{D}) = \int p(\mathbf{y} | \mathbf{x}, \mathbf{w}) \, p(\mathbf{w} | \mathbf{D}) \, d\mathbf{w}

We approximate the posterior over weights p(\mathbf{w}|\mathbf{D}) via variational inference with dropout:

\mathbf{w} \sim \text{Dropout}(\mathbf{w}_{\text{MAP}}, p_{\text{drop}})

For T stochastic forward passes (dropout enabled), the predictive mean and variance are:

\mathbb{E}[\mathbf{y}] \approx \frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=1}^T f(\mathbf{x}, \mathbf{w}_t), \quad
\text{Var}[\mathbf{y}] \approx \frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=1}^T f(\mathbf{x}, \mathbf{w}_t)^T f(\mathbf{x}, \mathbf{w}_t) - \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{y}]^T \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{y}]

Mathematical Justification (Convergence Proof): Gal & Ghahramani (2016) proved that dropout at inference induces a Bernoulli variational distribution q(\mathbf{w}) = \prod_i \text{Bernoulli}(p_i). The training objective with weight decay minimises the KL divergence between q(\mathbf{w}) and the true posterior p(\mathbf{w}|\mathbf{D}). By the Law of Large Numbers, as T \to \infty,

\frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=1}^T f(\mathbf{x}, \mathbf{w}_t) \xrightarrow{\text{a.s.}} \mathbb{E}_{q(\mathbf{w})}[f(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{w})]

and similarly for the second moment, yielding consistent estimates of the predictive mean and variance under the variational approximation.

Loss Function:

\mathcal{L} = -\frac{1}{N} \sum_{n=1}^N \log p(\mathbf{y}_n | \mathbf{x}_n, \mathbf{w}) + \text{KL}(q(\mathbf{w}) \,\|\, p(\mathbf{w})) + \lambda_{\text{phys}} \mathcal{L}_{\text{phys}}

where \mathcal{L}_{\text{phys}} = \max(0, -c) + \max(0, \phi - 50^\circ) penalises unphysical predictions.

Outputs: Probability density functions for duricrust thickness h \sim p(h|\mathbf{x}) and cohesion c \sim p(c|\mathbf{x}).

Multi‑Task Extension: The MMVT also predicts proxies for local porosity and ice‑content likelihood via known thermal‑inertia–ice correlations, feeding Tier 3’s priors on (c,\phi,\rho) and ice volume fraction.

4.4 Ablation Targets

Ablation studies will compare MMVT with/without the thermal/topographic branch and without the cross‑modal transformer (CTF), explicitly tying architecture decisions to physics reasoning (e.g., "thermal inertia alone is insufficient because of the thin duricrust–deep unconsolidated soil separation").

4.5 Validation Metrics

· Negative Log‑Likelihood (NLL);
· Expected Calibration Error (ECE) with reliability diagrams;
· Coverage Probability: fraction of held‑out InSight data falling within 95 % prediction intervals;
· Leave‑one‑site‑out Cross‑Validation: test on InSight, Phoenix, and Zhurong sites held out from training.

