6. Tier 3: Autonomous Adaptive Penetration

6.1 Objective

Design a computational architecture for a next‑generation penetrator to detect duricrust layers in real time (simulated) and autonomously adapt hammering strategy using only onboard sensor feedback.

6.2 Component 1: Momentum‑Conserving Graph‑Network Surrogate

Motivation: High‑fidelity DEM simulations are computationally prohibitive for real‑time control or RL training. Recent GNN surrogates achieve 100× to 2,900× speedups over conventional DEM while maintaining >93 % accuracy.

Why GNN > PINN > Eulerian Field Models: GNNs naturally encode granular contact topology and nonlocal effects, which are critical for cohesive, clumpy Mars regolith. Eulerian fields (finite‑difference, continuum) fail to capture the clump–cement–crack behaviour that trapped the HP³ mole.

Architecture: DYNAMI‑CAL GRAPHNET with Hard Momentum Conservation

We adopt the physics‑informed GNN architecture of Sharma & Fink (2026) that enforces pairwise conservation of linear and angular momentum through edge‑local reference frames. This approach is:

· Equivariant to rotational symmetries (SO(3) group);
· Invariant to translations;
· Equivariant to node permutations.

Graph Representation:
Granular material is represented as a graph \mathcal{G} = (\mathcal{V}, \mathcal{E}):

· Nodes \mathbf{v}_i \in \mathcal{V}: particle features [\mathbf{x}_i, \dot{\mathbf{x}}_i, \ddot{\mathbf{x}}_i, m_i, r_i] (position, velocity, acceleration, mass, radius);
· Edges \mathbf{e}_{ij} \in \mathcal{E}: contact features [\mathbf{d}_{ij}, \mathbf{n}_{ij}, |\mathbf{d}_{ij}|] (displacement vector, normal vector, distance).

Message Passing with Momentum Conservation:

1. Encoder:
   \mathbf{h}_i^0 = \text{MLP}_{\text{enc}}(\mathbf{v}_i), \quad \mathbf{h}_{ij}^0 = \text{MLP}_{\text{enc}}(\mathbf{e}_{ij})
2. Momentum‑Conserving Message Passing (K steps) :
   \mathbf{m}_{ij}^k = \text{MLP}_{\text{edge}}(\mathbf{h}_i^k, \mathbf{h}_j^k, \mathbf{h}_{ij}^k)
   Edge forces are constrained to be anti‑symmetric: \mathbf{F}_{ij} = -\mathbf{F}_{ji} (Newton’s Third Law). The node update enforces:
   \mathbf{h}_i^{k+1} = \text{MLP}_{\text{node}}\!\left(\mathbf{h}_i^k, \sum_{j \in \mathcal{N}(i)} \mathbf{m}_{ij}^k\right)
   with the constraints:
   \sum_i m_i \Delta \ddot{\mathbf{x}}_i = 0 \quad \text{(linear momentum)}, \qquad
   \sum_i \mathbf{r}_i \times (m_i \Delta \ddot{\mathbf{x}}_i) = 0 \quad \text{(angular momentum)}
   enforced via projection onto the null space of the constraint matrix.
3. Decoder: Predict particle accelerations:
   \hat{\ddot{\mathbf{x}}}_i = \text{MLP}_{\text{dec}}(\mathbf{h}_i^K)

Differentiability Proof: Automatic differentiation through MLP sums and projections is exact by the chain rule. The projection operator is linear and thus differentiable almost everywhere (except at measure‑zero boundaries where subgradients exist).

Long‑Rollout Stability Guarantee: Sharma & Fink (2026) empirically demonstrate that hard momentum conservation reduces error accumulation from \mathcal{O}(T) to \mathcal{O}(\sqrt{T}) in multi‑body dynamics, enabling stable rollouts over 10⁴ timesteps with >93 % accuracy. Lipschitz‑bounded MLPs (via spectral normalisation) ensure bounded error propagation.

Loss Function:

\mathcal{L}_{\text{GNS}} = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^N \|\hat{\ddot{\mathbf{x}}}_i - \ddot{\mathbf{x}}_i^{\text{DEM}}\|^2 + \lambda_{\text{contact}} \mathcal{L}_{\text{contact}}

where \mathcal{L}_{\text{contact}} = \max(0, r_i + r_j - |\mathbf{x}_{ij}|)^2 penalises particle interpenetration.

Scalability and Onboard Feasibility:
Current GNS implementations handle ≈2 \times 10^4 particles on 24 GB GPUs. For larger domains, we implement spatial decomposition with overlapping subgraphs (2–3 overlapping subgraphs per penetrator length, with 1–2 node‑width guard zones) and message passing across domain boundaries.

Onboard Deployment:
Target hardware: XQR Versal AI Core (XQRVC1902) — AMD’s space‑grade heterogeneous compute device qualified to MIL‑PRF‑38535 Class B in 2025. Features:

· ARM Cortex‑A72 application processors;
· AI Engines for ML acceleration;
· Large FPGA fabric for custom logic;
· 7 nm process, designed for LEO through deep space;
· Re‑programmable in‑flight.

Quantisation and Performance:

· 8‑bit integer quantisation reduces model size by 4×;
· N:M sparsity (2:4 pattern) further reduces FLOPs by 2×;
· hls4ml toolchain converts trained GNN to FPGA bitstream;
· Estimated inference latency: < 50 ms for 2k‑particle local window at < 10 W power consumption.

6.3 Component 2: Risk‑Sensitive Reinforcement Learning for Adaptive Control

Problem Formulation as POMDP:

· State \mathbf{s}_t: [a_{t-5:t}, \Delta z_{t-5:t}, F_{\text{hull},t}, N_{\text{strikes}}] (acceleration history, penetration rate, hull friction, strike count);
· Action \mathbf{a}_t: [f_{\text{hammer}}, E_{\text{strike}}, \tau_{\text{pause}}] (frequency, energy, pause duration);
· Reward r_t:
  r_t = \alpha \cdot \Delta z_t - \beta \cdot \mathbb{1}_{\text{bounce}} - \gamma \cdot \mathbb{1}_{\text{precession}} - \delta \cdot E_{\text{strike}} - \eta \cdot \text{Var}[\Delta z_t]
  where the final term penalises actions with high epistemic uncertainty (risk‑sensitive adjustment).

Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO) with Clipped Objective:

L^{\text{CLIP}}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_t\!\left[ \min\!\left( r_t(\theta) \hat{A}_t, \text{clip}(r_t(\theta), 1-\epsilon, 1+\epsilon) \hat{A}_t \right) \right]

where r_t(\theta) = \frac{\pi_\theta(a_t|s_t)}{\pi_{\theta_{\text{old}}}(a_t|s_t)} and \hat{A}_t is the Generalized Advantage Estimate.

Mathematical Guarantee (Monotonic Improvement) : Schulman et al. (2017) proved that PPO with KL penalty or clipping guarantees monotonic improvement in expected return under a trust‑region constraint:

\eta(\pi_{\text{new}}) \geq L_{\pi_{\text{old}}}(\pi_{\text{new}}) - \frac{4\epsilon\gamma}{(1-\gamma)^2} \alpha^2

where \alpha = \max_s D_{\text{KL}}(\pi_{\text{old}}(\cdot|s) \,\|\, \pi_{\text{new}}(\cdot|s)) and \epsilon = \max_{s,a} |A^\pi(s,a)|. The clipping mechanism ensures that \alpha remains bounded.

Risk‑Sensitive Lagrangian Extension:
VaR/CVaR are embedded as soft constraints via a Lagrangian penalty:

\max_{\pi} \mathbb{E}[R] - \lambda \max(0, \text{VaR}_{\alpha} - d_{\text{min}})

so the policy avoids "deep‑but‑risky" strategies that occasionally fail catastrophically.

Domain Randomisation for Sim2Real Transfer:
To mitigate the simulation‑to‑reality gap without physical testing, we randomise during training:

· Cohesion c \sim \mathcal{U}(0, 25) kPa;
· Friction angle \phi \sim \mathcal{U}(20^\circ, 45^\circ);
· Grain size distribution \sim \text{lognormal}(\mu, \sigma);
· Duricrust thickness h \sim \mathcal{U}(5, 50) cm;
· Penetrator initial tilt \theta_0 \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 2^\circ).

Environment Encoder for Rapid Adaptation:
A GRU encoder network q(\mathbf{z} | \mathbf{s}_{t-k:t}) learns a latent representation of current soil conditions from recent penetration history, enabling the policy to adapt without explicit parameter identification. The latent variable \mathbf{z} is concatenated with the state before policy and value function computation.

6.4 Validation

· GNS vs. High‑Fidelity DEM: particle position MSE and speedup factor on held‑out DEM simulations (LIGGGHTS/YADE). Metrics: 10‑step rollout error and 1000‑step long‑horizon error.
· Momentum Conservation Error: drift in total linear and angular momentum over extended rollouts.
· RL Policy vs. Baseline: final penetration depth, time‑to‑target, and number of anomalous events (bounce‑back, precession) against constant‑hammering HP³ baseline on 100 randomised soil profiles.
· Failure Probability (Value‑at‑Risk) : compute \text{VaR}_{\alpha} = \inf\{z : P(\text{depth} \leq z) \geq \alpha\} and \text{CVaR}_{\alpha} = \mathbb{E}[\text{depth} \mid \text{depth} \leq \text{VaR}_{\alpha}] to quantify tail risk.

