Appendix A: Mathematical Foundations

A.1 Penetration Mechanics and Regolith Properties

A.1.1 Governing Equations for Mole Penetration

The HP³ mole penetration dynamics are governed by the balance between hammering force and resisting soil friction. The mole advances when the frictional force F_f from surrounding soil exceeds the net recoil force F_r from the hammer mechanism. Under nominal conditions:

F_f = \mu_s \cdot N

where \mu_s is the soil-mole interface friction coefficient and N is the normal force from soil confinement.

The normal force arises from the radial stress \sigma_r exerted by the regolith on the mole hull. For a cohesionless granular material, the radial stress follows the Janssen equation for silo pressure:

\sigma_r(z) = K_0 \gamma z

where K_0 is the coefficient of lateral earth pressure at rest (K_0 \approx 1 - \sin\phi), \gamma is the soil unit weight, and z is depth.

For cohesive duricrust, the Mohr-Coulomb failure criterion applies:

\tau_f = c + \sigma_n \tan\phi

where \tau_f is shear strength, c is cohesion, \sigma_n is normal stress, and \phi is internal friction angle.

A.1.2 Cone Penetration Resistance

The penetration resistance q_c measured by the HP³ mole can be related to soil parameters using cone penetration theory:

q_c = N_c c + N_q \sigma_v

where N_c and N_q are bearing capacity factors dependent on \phi, and \sigma_v is the vertical effective stress. The InSight HP³ measurements yielded:

· Duricrust (0–20 cm depth): q_c = 0.3\text{–}0.7 MPa
· Deeper layer (>30 cm): q_c = 4.9 \pm 0.4 MPa
· Estimated cohesion: c = 2\text{–}15 kPa (depending on assumed \phi)
· Scoop blade chopping estimate: c \approx 5.8 kPa

Source: The NASA InSight Lander includes the Heat Flow and Physical Properties Package HP³, with the mole requiring friction on its hull to balance recoil from its hammer mechanism. The root cause of the failure was a lack of friction in an unexpectedly thick cohesive duricrust. The penetration record was used to infer mechanical soil parameters such as the penetration resistance of the duricrust of 0.3–0.7 MPa and a penetration resistance of a deeper layer (>30 cm depth) of 4.9 \pm 0.4 MPa. Applying cone penetration theory, the resistance of the duricrust was used to estimate a cohesion of 2–15 kPa depending on the internal friction angle. Pushing the scoop with its blade into the surface and chopping off a piece of duricrust provided another estimate of the cohesion of 5.8 kPa.

A.1.3 Thermal Properties and Duricrust Formation

The duricrust formation mechanism is tied to brine efflorescence. Thermal conductivity measurements from the HP³ mole sensors revealed:

· Surface sand layer (1 cm): k \approx 14 mW/(m·K)
· Duricrust and underlying sand: k \approx 34 mW/(m·K)
· Gravel layer below: k \approx 64 mW/(m·K)

The thermal conductivity variations correlate strongly with atmospheric pressure (6.5% per mbar), characteristic of unconsolidated material with gas-phase conduction contributions. This apparent contradiction with the cohesive duricrust is resolved by recognizing that the duricrust is a thin, cemented surface layer that disaggregated during initial penetration attempts, while deeper material presents high resistance due to confining pressure and grain packing rather than cementation.

Source: The combined data suggest a model of the regolith that has an about 20 cm thick duricrust underneath a 1 cm thick sand layer and above another 10 cm of sand. Underneath the latter, a layer more resistant to penetration and possibly consisting of debris from a small impact crater was found. The thermal conductivity increases from 14 mW/m K in the 1 cm sand layer to 34 mW/m K in the duricrust and the sand layer underneath the duricrust to 64 mW/m K in the gravel layer below.

A.2 Terramechanics: Bekker-Wong and Ishigami-Reece Models

A.2.1 Bekker Pressure-Sinkage Relationship

The Bekker model describes normal pressure p as a function of sinkage z:

p(z) = \left(\frac{k_c}{b} + k_\phi\right) z^n

where:

· k_c: cohesive modulus of soil deformation
· k_\phi: frictional modulus of soil deformation
· b: wheel width or contact dimension
· n: pressure-sinkage exponent (typically 0.7–1.3 for sands)

A.2.2 Ishigami-Reece Shear Stress Model

The shear stress \tau at the wheel-soil interface is:

\tau(\theta) = (c + \sigma(\theta) \tan\phi) \left(1 - e^{-j(\theta)/K}\right)

where:

· \sigma(\theta): normal stress at angle \theta
· j(\theta): shear displacement
· K: shear deformation modulus

A.2.3 Wheel Slip and Drawbar Pull

The slip ratio s is defined as:

s = 1 - \frac{v_x}{r\omega} \quad \text{(driving)} \quad \text{or} \quad s = \frac{r\omega}{v_x} - 1 \quad \text{(braking)}

where v_x is forward velocity, r is wheel radius, and \omega is angular velocity.

The drawbar pull DP (net traction) is:

DP = \int (\tau \cos\theta - \sigma \sin\theta) \, dA

and resisting torque T is:

T = r \int \tau \, dA

A.3 Graph Network-based Simulator (GNS) Mathematical Framework

A.3.1 Graph Representation of Granular Material

The GNS framework represents the state of a physical system with particles, expressed as nodes in a graph, and computes dynamics via learned message-passing. Our framework—which we term "Graph Network-based Simulators" (GNS)—represents the state of a physical system with particles, expressed as nodes in a graph, and computes dynamics via learned message-passing.

A granular material is represented as a directed graph \mathcal{G} = (\mathcal{V}, \mathcal{E}):

Nodes \mathbf{v}_i \in \mathcal{V} with features:

\mathbf{v}_i = [\mathbf{x}_i, \dot{\mathbf{x}}_i, \ddot{\mathbf{x}}_i^{\text{prev}}, m_i, r_i, \text{type}_i]

where:

· \mathbf{x}_i \in \mathbb{R}^3: position
· \dot{\mathbf{x}}_i \in \mathbb{R}^3: velocity
· \ddot{\mathbf{x}}_i^{\text{prev}} \in \mathbb{R}^3: previous acceleration (for temporal context)
· m_i: mass
· r_i: radius
· \text{type}_i: particle type (static/mobile, soil/penetrator)

Edges \mathbf{e}_{ij} \in \mathcal{E} connect particles within interaction radius R_c:

\mathcal{E} = \{(i,j) : \|\mathbf{x}_i - \mathbf{x}_j\| \leq R_c\}

Edge features:

\mathbf{e}_{ij} = [\mathbf{d}_{ij}, \|\mathbf{d}_{ij}\|, \mathbf{n}_{ij}]

where \mathbf{d}_{ij} = \mathbf{x}_i - \mathbf{x}_j (displacement vector) and \mathbf{n}_{ij} = \mathbf{d}_{ij} / \|\mathbf{d}_{ij}\| (unit normal).

A.3.2 Message Passing with Hard Momentum Conservation (DYNAMI-CAL GRAPHNET)

The physics-informed GNN architecture enforces pairwise conservation of linear and angular momentum for interacting nodes using edge-local reference frames that are equivariant to rotational symmetries, invariant to translations, and equivariant to node permutations.

Encoder:

\mathbf{h}_i^0 = \text{MLP}_{\text{enc}}(\mathbf{v}_i), \quad \mathbf{h}_{ij}^0 = \text{MLP}_{\text{edge}}(\mathbf{e}_{ij})

Message Passing (K steps):
For each edge (i,j), compute message:

\mathbf{m}_{ij}^k = \text{MLP}_{\text{msg}}(\mathbf{h}_i^k, \mathbf{h}_j^k, \mathbf{h}_{ij}^k)

Enforce Newton's Third Law (anti-symmetric forces):

\mathbf{F}_{ij} = -\mathbf{F}_{ji} \quad \text{(explicit constraint)}

Node update with momentum conservation constraints:

\mathbf{h}_i^{k+1} = \text{MLP}_{\text{node}}\left(\mathbf{h}_i^k, \sum_{j \in \mathcal{N}(i)} \mathbf{m}_{ij}^k\right)

subject to:

\sum_i m_i \Delta\ddot{\mathbf{x}}_i = 0 \quad \text{(linear momentum)}

\sum_i \mathbf{r}_i \times (m_i \Delta\ddot{\mathbf{x}}_i) = 0 \quad \text{(angular momentum)}

These constraints are enforced via projection onto the null space of the constraint matrix.

Decoder:

\hat{\ddot{\mathbf{x}}}_i = \text{MLP}_{\text{dec}}(\mathbf{h}_i^K)

Loss Function:

\mathcal{L}_{\text{GNS}} = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^N \|\hat{\ddot{\mathbf{x}}}_i - \ddot{\mathbf{x}}_i^{\text{DEM}}\|^2 + \lambda_{\text{contact}} \max(0, r_i + r_j - \|\mathbf{d}_{ij}\|)^2

A.3.3 Edge-Local Reference Frames

For rotational equivariance, edge-local coordinate frames are constructed:

\hat{\mathbf{e}}_1 = \frac{\mathbf{d}_{ij}}{\|\mathbf{d}_{ij}\|}, \quad
\hat{\mathbf{e}}_2 = \frac{\mathbf{v}_{\text{rel}} - (\mathbf{v}_{\text{rel}} \cdot \hat{\mathbf{e}}_1)\hat{\mathbf{e}}_1}{\|\mathbf{v}_{\text{rel}} - (\mathbf{v}_{\text{rel}} \cdot \hat{\mathbf{e}}_1)\hat{\mathbf{e}}_1\|}, \quad
\hat{\mathbf{e}}_3 = \hat{\mathbf{e}}_1 \times \hat{\mathbf{e}}_2

This construction ensures that edge messages are invariant to global rotations and translations.

A.4 Multi-Fidelity Deep Gaussian Processes (MF-DGP)

A.4.1 Gaussian Process Regression

A Gaussian Process defines a distribution over functions f(\mathbf{x}) \sim \mathcal{GP}(m(\mathbf{x}), k(\mathbf{x}, \mathbf{x}')), with mean function m(\mathbf{x}) and covariance kernel k(\mathbf{x}, \mathbf{x}'). For regression with training data \{\mathbf{X}, \mathbf{y}\} and Gaussian noise \sigma_n^2:

\mathbf{f}_* | \mathbf{X}_*, \mathbf{X}, \mathbf{y} \sim \mathcal{N}(\boldsymbol{\mu}_*, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_*)

\boldsymbol{\mu}_* = \mathbf{K}_{*}^T (\mathbf{K} + \sigma_n^2 \mathbf{I})^{-1} \mathbf{y}

\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_* = \mathbf{K}_{**} - \mathbf{K}_{*}^T (\mathbf{K} + \sigma_n^2 \mathbf{I})^{-1} \mathbf{K}_{*}

A.4.2 Sparse Variational GP (SVGP) with Inducing Points

For large datasets (N large), the SVGP approximation with M \ll N inducing points \mathbf{Z} reduces computational complexity from \mathcal{O}(N^3) to \mathcal{O}(NM^2). The Nyström approximation:

\mathbf{K}_{NN} \approx \mathbf{K}_{NM} \mathbf{K}_{MM}^{-1} \mathbf{K}_{MN}

The variational ELBO to maximize is:

\mathcal{L}_{\text{ELBO}} = \sum_{i=1}^N \mathbb{E}_{q(f_i)}[\log p(y_i | f_i)] - \text{KL}(q(\mathbf{u}) \| p(\mathbf{u} | \mathbf{Z}))

where \mathbf{u} = f(\mathbf{Z}) are inducing point values and q(\mathbf{u}) = \mathcal{N}(\mathbf{u} | \mathbf{m}, \mathbf{S}).

A.4.3 Multi-Fidelity Deep GP Architecture

The multi-fidelity DGP models a hierarchy of fidelities, where each layer corresponds to a different fidelity level:

f_\ell(\mathbf{x}) = g_\ell(\mathbf{x}, f_{\ell-1}(\mathbf{x}))

For terramechanical modeling, the fidelity levels are:

· Level 1 (Low): Bekker-Wong analytical model
· Level 2 (Medium): Soil Contact Model (SCM) simulation
· Level 3 (High): Discrete Element Method (DEM) simulation

The multi-fidelity Gaussian Process surrogate model is designed to predict the dynamic interactions between wheels and soft soil, including the forces and torques acting on the wheel. Specifically, it focuses on the prediction of forces and torques acting on the wheel during motion.

The training objective incorporates data from all fidelity levels:

p(\mathbf{y}_L | \mathbf{x}) \approx \int \prod_{\ell=1}^L p(\mathbf{y}_\ell | f_\ell) p(f_\ell | f_{\ell-1}) \, df_{1:L-1}

A.5 Bayesian Inference and Uncertainty Quantification

A.5.1 Variational Inference with Monte Carlo Dropout

Monte Carlo Dropout approximates the posterior over network weights via variational inference. Given a neural network with dropout applied at training and inference, the predictive distribution is:

p(\mathbf{y} | \mathbf{x}, \mathbf{D}) = \int p(\mathbf{y} | \mathbf{x}, \mathbf{w}) p(\mathbf{w} | \mathbf{D}) \, d\mathbf{w} \approx \frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=1}^T p(\mathbf{y} | \mathbf{x}, \mathbf{w}_t)

where \mathbf{w}_t \sim q(\mathbf{w}) are sampled via dropout.

The variational objective is:

\mathcal{L}_{\text{VI}} = -\frac{1}{N} \sum_{n=1}^N \log p(\mathbf{y}_n | \mathbf{x}_n, \mathbf{w}) + \text{KL}(q(\mathbf{w}) \| p(\mathbf{w}))

This technique transforms any dropout-trained neural network into a Bayesian approximation for uncertainty quantification. The Monte Carlo Dropout method allows production of the posterior distribution of the network weights by training a dropout network that approximates Bayesian inference.

A.5.2 Predictive Mean and Variance

For T stochastic forward passes with dropout enabled:

\mathbb{E}[\mathbf{y}] \approx \frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=1}^T f(\mathbf{x}, \mathbf{w}_t)

\text{Var}[\mathbf{y}] \approx \frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=1}^T f(\mathbf{x}, \mathbf{w}_t)^2 - \left(\frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=1}^T f(\mathbf{x}, \mathbf{w}_t)\right)^2 + \sigma_{\text{aleatoric}}^2

where \sigma_{\text{aleatoric}}^2 captures inherent observation noise.

A.5.3 Expected Calibration Error (ECE)

To assess calibration quality, predictions are binned by confidence:

\text{ECE} = \sum_{m=1}^M \frac{|B_m|}{N} \left| \text{acc}(B_m) - \text{conf}(B_m) \right|

where B_m is the set of samples in bin m, \text{acc}(B_m) is observed accuracy, and \text{conf}(B_m) is average predicted confidence.

A.6 Reinforcement Learning: PPO Mathematical Formulation

A.6.1 POMDP Definition

The penetration control problem is formulated as a Partially Observable Markov Decision Process (POMDP) with:

· State space \mathcal{S}: \mathbf{s}_t = [a_{t-5:t}, \Delta z_{t-5:t}, F_{\text{hull},t}, N_{\text{strikes}}]
· Action space \mathcal{A}: \mathbf{a}_t = [f_{\text{hammer}}, E_{\text{strike}}, \tau_{\text{pause}}]
· Reward function r(\mathbf{s}, \mathbf{a}): r_t = \alpha \Delta z_t - \beta \mathbb{1}_{\text{bounce}} - \gamma \mathbb{1}_{\text{precession}} - \delta E_{\text{strike}} - \eta \text{Var}[\Delta z_t]
· Discount factor \gamma \in (0,1)

A.6.2 PPO Clipped Surrogate Objective

Proximal Policy Optimization algorithm employing a clipped surrogate objective (PPO-Clip) is a prominent exemplar of the policy optimization methods.

The PPO objective is:

L^{\text{CLIP}}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_t \left[ \min\left( r_t(\theta) \hat{A}_t, \text{clip}(r_t(\theta), 1-\epsilon, 1+\epsilon) \hat{A}_t \right) \right]

where:

· r_t(\theta) = \frac{\pi_\theta(a_t|s_t)}{\pi_{\theta_{\text{old}}}(a_t|s_t)} (probability ratio)
· \hat{A}_t is the Generalized Advantage Estimate (GAE)
· \epsilon is the clipping parameter (typically 0.1–0.2)

A.6.3 Generalized Advantage Estimation (GAE)

\hat{A}_t = \sum_{l=0}^{\infty} (\gamma \lambda)^l \delta_{t+l}

\delta_t = r_t + \gamma V(s_{t+1}) - V(s_t)

where \lambda \in [0,1] controls the bias-variance trade-off.

A.6.4 Value Function Loss

L^{\text{VF}}(\phi) = \mathbb{E}_t \left[ \left( V_\phi(s_t) - V_t^{\text{target}} \right)^2 \right]

where V_t^{\text{target}} = \hat{A}_t + V_{\phi_{\text{old}}}(s_t).

A.6.5 Total PPO Loss

L^{\text{PPO}}(\theta, \phi) = \mathbb{E}_t \left[ -L^{\text{CLIP}}(\theta) + c_1 L^{\text{VF}}(\phi) - c_2 H[\pi_\theta](\cdot | s_t) \right]

where H[\pi_\theta] is an entropy bonus encouraging exploration, and c_1, c_2 are coefficients.

A.7 Cross-Modal Transformer Fusion

A.7.1 Multi-Head Self-Attention

The transformer architecture uses multi-head self-attention:

\text{Attention}(Q, K, V) = \text{softmax}\left(\frac{QK^T}{\sqrt{d_k}}\right)V

For multi-head attention with h heads:

\text{MultiHead}(Q, K, V) = \text{Concat}(\text{head}_1, \ldots, \text{head}_h) W^O

\text{head}_i = \text{Attention}(QW_i^Q, KW_i^K, VW_i^V)

A.7.2 Cross-Modal Fusion Strategy

A transformer-based feature extraction and cross-modal fusion strategy is adopted, where infrared imagery guides the interaction among multi-source features.

For modalities \mathbf{Z}_1 (vision), \mathbf{Z}_2 (spectral), and \mathbf{Z}_3 (thermal):

\mathbf{Z}_{\text{fused}} = \text{CrossAttention}(\mathbf{Z}_1, \mathbf{Z}_2, \mathbf{Z}_3)

where CrossAttention implements cross-modal queries:

Q = \mathbf{Z}_1 W^Q, \quad K = [\mathbf{Z}_2; \mathbf{Z}_3] W^K, \quad V = [\mathbf{Z}_2; \mathbf{Z}_3] W^V

A.7.3 Positional Encoding

Sinusoidal positional encodings are used for spatial awareness:

PE_{(pos, 2i)} = \sin\left(\frac{pos}{10000^{2i/d_{\text{model}}}}\right)

PE_{(pos, 2i+1)} = \cos\left(\frac{pos}{10000^{2i/d_{\text{model}}}}\right)

