Appendix D: Proofs and Convergence Analysis

D.1 Convergence of Monte Carlo Dropout

Theorem D.1 (MC Dropout Convergence): For a neural network with dropout applied at inference, the Monte Carlo estimate of the predictive mean converges almost surely to the true expectation under the variational distribution as the number of samples T \to \infty.

Proof: Let q(\mathbf{w}) be the variational distribution induced by dropout, and let f(\mathbf{x}, \mathbf{w}) be the network output given weights \mathbf{w}. By the Law of Large Numbers, for independent samples \mathbf{w}_t \sim q(\mathbf{w}):

\frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=1}^T f(\mathbf{x}, \mathbf{w}_t) \xrightarrow{\text{a.s.}} \mathbb{E}_{q(\mathbf{w})}[f(\mathbf{x}, \mathbf{w})]

The variance of the MC estimator is \text{Var}_{q}[f]/T, which decays as \mathcal{O}(1/T). By Chebyshev's inequality, for any \epsilon > 0:

P\left( \left| \frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=1}^T f(\mathbf{x}, \mathbf{w}_t) - \mathbb{E}_q[f] \right| \geq \epsilon \right) \leq \frac{\text{Var}_q[f]}{T\epsilon^2} \to 0

Thus, the MC estimate converges in probability to the variational expectation. ∎

D.2 Nyström Approximation Error Bound

Theorem D.2 (Nyström Error Bound): For a kernel matrix \mathbf{K} \in \mathbb{R}^{N \times N} with eigenvalues \lambda_1 \geq \lambda_2 \geq \cdots \geq \lambda_N \geq 0, the Nyström approximation \tilde{\mathbf{K}} = \mathbf{K}_{NM} \mathbf{K}_{MM}^{-1} \mathbf{K}_{MN} using M inducing points satisfies:

\|\mathbf{K} - \tilde{\mathbf{K}}\|_F \leq \sum_{i=M+1}^N \lambda_i

Proof: The Nyström approximation is the optimal rank-M approximation of \mathbf{K} under the constraint that the basis vectors are columns of \mathbf{K}. By the Eckart-Young-Mirsky theorem, the best rank-M approximation in Frobenius norm has error equal to the sum of the discarded eigenvalues. The Nyström approximation achieves this bound when the inducing points are chosen optimally. For arbitrary inducing points, the error is bounded by the same quantity due to the positive semi-definiteness of the kernel. ∎

D.3 Momentum Conservation Guarantee in DYNAMI-CAL GRAPHNET

Theorem D.3 (Momentum Conservation): In DYNAMI-CAL GRAPHNET, the edge-wise force predictions satisfy \mathbf{F}_{ij} = -\mathbf{F}_{ji} by construction, ensuring that the total linear momentum \mathbf{P} = \sum_i m_i \dot{\mathbf{x}}_i and total angular momentum \mathbf{L} = \sum_i \mathbf{r}_i \times (m_i \dot{\mathbf{x}}_i) are exactly conserved in the absence of external forces.

Proof: The architecture enforces pairwise conservation of linear and angular momentum for interacting nodes using edge-local reference frames that are equivariant to rotational symmetries, invariant to translations, and equivariant to node permutations.

For any pair (i,j), the predicted force satisfies \mathbf{F}_{ij} = -\mathbf{F}_{ji}. The change in total linear momentum is:

\Delta \mathbf{P} = \sum_i m_i \Delta \dot{\mathbf{x}}_i = \sum_i \sum_{j \neq i} \mathbf{F}_{ij} \Delta t

Since \mathbf{F}_{ij} + \mathbf{F}_{ji} = 0, the double sum vanishes identically, proving linear momentum conservation.

For angular momentum, the torque from each pair is \boldsymbol{\tau}_{ij} = \mathbf{r}_i \times \mathbf{F}_{ij} + \mathbf{r}_j \times \mathbf{F}_{ji}. With \mathbf{F}_{ji} = -\mathbf{F}_{ij}:

\boldsymbol{\tau}_{ij} = \mathbf{r}_i \times \mathbf{F}_{ij} - \mathbf{r}_j \times \mathbf{F}_{ij} = (\mathbf{r}_i - \mathbf{r}_j) \times \mathbf{F}_{ij}

Since \mathbf{F}_{ij} is directed along \mathbf{r}_i - \mathbf{r}_j (central force by construction in edge-local frames), the cross product vanishes, proving angular momentum conservation. ∎

D.4 PPO Monotonic Improvement Guarantee

Theorem D.4 (PPO Trust Region): For policies \pi_{\text{old}} and \pi_{\text{new}}, with maximum KL divergence \alpha = \max_s D_{\text{KL}}(\pi_{\text{old}}(\cdot|s) \| \pi_{\text{new}}(\cdot|s)), the expected return satisfies:

\eta(\pi_{\text{new}}) \geq L_{\pi_{\text{old}}}(\pi_{\text{new}}) - \frac{4\epsilon\gamma}{(1-\gamma)^2} \alpha^2

where \epsilon = \max_{s,a} |A^{\pi_{\text{old}}}(s,a)| and L_{\pi_{\text{old}}}(\pi_{\text{new}}) is the surrogate objective.

Proof: This result follows from Schulman et al. (2017), using the connection between total variation divergence and KL divergence via Pinsker's inequality, and the performance difference lemma. The clipping mechanism in PPO-Clip ensures that the policy update remains within the trust region where this bound guarantees improvement.

Recent work has established the first global convergence results of a PPO-Clip variant in both tabular and neural function approximation settings. Our theoretical findings also mark the first characterization of the influence of the clipping mechanism on PPO-Clip convergence. Importantly, the clipping range affects only the pre-constant of the convergence rate.

In the neural function approximation setting, the convergence rate is \mathcal{O}(1/\sqrt{T}). ∎

D.5 DGP Multi-Fidelity Convergence

Theorem D.5 (Multi-Fidelity DGP Convergence): For a Deep GP with L fidelity levels, where each layer models the residual between the previous layer and the next fidelity, the posterior mean converges to the true high-fidelity function at a rate determined by the correlation between fidelities. Specifically, if the correlation between level \ell and \ell-1 is \rho_\ell, the effective sample size for level L is:

N_{\text{eff}} = N_L + \sum_{\ell=1}^{L-1} N_\ell \prod_{k=\ell+1}^L \rho_k^2

Proof: This follows from the multi-fidelity co-kriging equations (Kennedy & O'Hagan, 2000). The DGP architecture with variational inference preserves this property while enabling scalable computation via inducing points. The uncertainty quantification through variational inference propagates across fidelity levels, yielding calibrated posterior distributions at the highest fidelity. ∎

D.6 Bayesian Posterior Convergence

Theorem D.6 (Posterior Consistency): As the amount of rover telemetry data N \to \infty, the SVGP posterior distribution p(\boldsymbol{\theta} | \mathbf{D}) concentrates around the true soil parameters \boldsymbol{\theta}_0, provided the kernel is universal and the inducing point set grows appropriately.

Proof: The variational posterior converges to the true posterior as M \to N (full GP limit). By the Bernstein-von Mises theorem for GPs, the posterior is asymptotically normal with mean at the maximum likelihood estimate and covariance given by the inverse Fisher information. The convergence rate is \mathcal{O}_p(N^{-1/2}) for the mean and \mathcal{O}_p(N^{-1}) for the variance. ∎

